**The only part of Zero worth taking for Omo-Koda2 is its structured error and repair format.**

Zero forces every compilation error and diagnostic into clean, machine-readable JSON that an AI agent can actually act on. That pattern fits your architecture perfectly — especially in the **Rust steward core** and **Osovm**.

You could adapt this so that every time something fails in any of your languages (Julia, Python, Lisp, Move, etc.), Osovm or the Rust core spits out the same structured JSON shape. That way your agent can reliably read the error, understand it, and fix it — no matter which language threw it.

Everything else in Zero — the language syntax, the tiny binary size, the effects system — doesn't map cleanly to your multi-language fractal design. Just steal the **structured diagnostics and repair plan format**. It's small, focused, and actually useful to you.

What about Move and adding that with gh repo clone Bino-Elgua/Zangbeto

**Yes, you can and should include Move.**

Here's how it fits cleanly:

**Move’s role for this concept:**  
Since Move runs on-chain (Sui), it should emit the same structured diagnostic format when transactions fail, when receipts are invalid, or when economic rules (staking, slashing, royalties) are violated. This lets your agent understand on-chain errors the same way it understands Rust or Julia errors.

**Recommended approach:**

- Keep the **canonical schema** defined in your Rust crate (`omo-diagnostic`).
- In Zangbeto (which is your security/audit layer), add validation logic that checks whether Move errors conform to that same format.
- When you run `gh repo clone Bino-Elgua/Zangbeto`, treat it as the guardian that enforces this contract across *all* languages, including Move.

So the full flow becomes:  
Rust defines the format → Every language (including Move) must output it → Zangbeto audits and enforces it.

**The only part of Zero worth taking for Omo-Koda2 is its structured error and repair format.**

Zero forces every compilation error and diagnostic into clean, machine-readable JSON that an AI agent can actually act on. That pattern fits your architecture perfectly — especially in the **Rust steward core** and **Osovm**.

You could adapt this so that every time something fails in any of your languages (Julia, Python, Lisp, Move, etc.), Osovm or the Rust core spits out the same structured JSON shape. That way your agent can reliably read the error, understand it, and fix it — no matter which language threw it.


